name: Jeremy Chen
tweet: So, we can combine these insights to say this: 1) God intended for Jesus to express God's wrath against evil by overcoming death's power w/ his love that survived through his unjust, state-sponsored execution on the cross into resurrection life.

name: Jeremy Chen
tweet: By remaining faithful to the point of his gruesome death, Jesus extinguish's sin's power and purifies his human nature. He completes his human purpose, allowing the object of God's anger - the injustice God hates, to be destroyed in Jesus' embodiment of evil-defeating-love.

name: Jeremy Chen
tweet: As for (2), let's think abt wrath/anger/rage. Righteous anger results when what one loves has been unjustly wounded. Out-of-control Anger desires revenge, to vent that wrath through a channel of destruction. Productive wrath desires for the evil itself to be destroyed.

name: Jeremy Chen
tweet: As such, the affirmations in the book of Acts, for instance, that God planned for Jesus to suffer/die on the cross can be true without entailing that God executed Jesus. God's intentions/ activity in empowering Jesus through his faithful death aren't identical w/ that of Rome.
